  1489	Mike- I won't argue. Personally, I can see many reasons for keeping it broad
  1490	as far as platform goes, I mean, you could make a good case that the Amiga is
  1491	the way to go here! I have DKB,for example, which was originally developed FOR
  1492	the Amiga, and then ported to DOS by Aaron Collins. So I understand, your
  1493	point is well taken, believe me. I won't sit here trying to tell everyone that
  1494	DOS is it, like it or leave it.  That would be, quite simply, nothing short of
  1495	foolish. I do think,  however, that it IS important to remember that DOS is
  1496	the closest thing there is to a "defacto" OS there is. That's nothing against
  1497	other platforms, I would like to have an Amiga and a Mac in addition to my
  1498	286.  Also, please read my opening messages to the section, you will notice I
  1499	proposed using C for projects. One of the reasons, I don't think it's
  1500	necessary to point out, is portability of code (up to a point, at least).
  1501	Relax. No one is going to get left out here. Besides,  the more I think about
  1502	it, and the more I read in the messages from people who are miles beyond me
  1503	technically, I think a card is probably unnecessary after all. Using serial
  1504	and parallel ports will probably do.  When things DO get platform-specific,
  1505	can I take your message as an offer to help make developing code work on
  1506	different platforms? There is no reason why we can't have parallel projects
  1507	going on, anyway; but a little bit of unified effort is important, so we can
  1508	get the most from our collected resources.  Nothing is fixed yet, so hang in
  1509	there, and most important, keep telling me what you think.
  1510	JLE 
