  1539	#: 21538 S13/Virtual Reality
  1540	    13-Nov-91  20:54:48
  1541	Sb: #Position Sensors
  1542	Fm: Alexander Schipal 76137,326
  1543	To: All
  1544	
  1545	
  1546	Last year I asked a friend who is an engineer at a British aerospace company
  1547	about the availability of laser gyros. He smiled and said, yep, they are
  1548	available, weigh only 20 pounds and cost a mere $100K.
  1549	
  1550	A few weeks ago, there was a tiny notice on Business Week's "New Technology"
  1551	page about an upstart company that makes a cheap ($500) and tiny (2 oz.)
  1552	gyroscope. Given the size and weight, it MUST be a laser gyro. As a first
  1553	application, they are doing a 3D mouse. The company's name is Gyration Inc. 
  1554	No address was given.
  1555	
  1556	If this thing works with reasonable speed and precision, it is exactly the
  1557	kind of position sensor VR needs ! Other than the currently used magnetic and
  1558	ultrasound sensors, a gyro would not need a transmitter reference point that
  1559	has a data link to the receiver, and there is NO RANGE LIMITATION.  It could
  1560	even be used for a mobile/outdoors VR system.
  1561	
  1562	Question: Where is Gyration Inc ?
  1563	
