  1603	
  1604	
  1605	The VR demo program in the library shows what is probably the best you can do
  1606	with a standard PC without any hardware accelerator: a few hundred polygons
  1607	per second, no Gouraud shading, no texturing. Frankly, that isn't very
  1608	impressive. With this level of performance, VR isn't even good for games.
  1609	
  1610	VR needs VERY fast 3D rendering, and a "naked" PC/Amiga/Atari/Mac simply does
  1611	not have the MIPs that it takes.
  1612	
  1613	To get a discussion going, I'll list some possible PC-based rendering engines:
  1614	
  1615	1) Intel DVI card Used by Sense8 for the WorldToolKit. The 750 processor seems
  1616	to be pretty good at texture mapping, but has no FPU. Still no Gouraud shading
  1617	and low polygon count, but the polygons can be phototextured.  Stuff like a
  1618	triangle with a "fir tree" texture or a square with an "oriental rug" pattern
  1619	makes a virtual world look pretty good.  DVI cards are readily available and
  1620	do double duty as multimedia hardware in Multimedia Windows. They also have a
  1621	very good audio section.
  1622	
  1623	2) Transputer (net) + frame buffer My personal favourite. Transputers are not
  1624	very popular in the US (not-invented-here syndrome?), but the new T9000 chips
  1625	are the ONLY way to do fancy stuff like realtime raytracing. A single T9000
  1626	has about 100 MIPs, and an arbitrary number of T9000s can be connected in
  1627	multiprocessing transputer nets by four 100mbps packet-switching data links
  1628	integrated on the chip.Extremely high performance + unlimited scaleabilty !
  1629	Transputer boards are also easy to layout (few glue chips).
  1630	
  1631	3) 80860 + frame buffer Very fast FPU with special 3D-oriented instructions
  1632	that facilitate shading and Z-buffering.
  1633	
  1634	4) Graphics processors Division has an 80860 board that offloads shading to a
  1635	High Speed Shading Processor (AFAIK, made by Sharp). It is said to shade twice
  1636	as fast as the 80860. Maybe a HSSP-only board is worth a try.
  1637	
  1638	5) ASICs What about a few nifty FPGAs ? Dream on...
  1639	
  1640	There are 2 Replies.
  1641	
