  1684	#: 21555 S13/Virtual Reality
  1685	    14-Nov-91  06:02:04
  1686	Sb: 3D glasses
  1687	Fm: John Swenson 75300,2136
  1688	To: Mike Schoenborn 70010,147 (X)
  1689	
  1690	Mike,
  1691	(in accordance with John's message this is now a new thread)
  1692	Thats great that it can actually be made to transmit a lot more light, I'll
  1693	have to wait to get mine before I can talk intelligently about them though.
  1694	 
  1695	I was thinking about tweaking the VGA timing such that you used as fast a
  1696	vertical refresh rate as your board and monitor can take. For 640 x 480 and
  1697	lower on the Ergo that means 90Hz (which is the fastest most monitors can
  1698	do). That should have considerably less flicker than what you get out of
  1699	"normal" modes. Another approach would be to use a builtin interlaced mode,
  1700	and alternate the lines from the two images in the video ram, you wouldn't
  1701	have to do ANYTHING to the VGA then, just make sure that the glasses are
  1702	syncronized with the vertical rate. It wouldn't cut down on the flicker, but
  1703	the software would not need to tweak the VGA.
  1704	 
  1705	 
  1706	I was talking to friend at work about this and he came up with a nice
  1707	solution which might work. Switch the glasses in two or three places during
  1708	the drawing of the scan, and interleave the eyes on one image, then have the
  1709	other image use the oposite eye interleaving. The only problem with this is
  1710	that the glasses might not change fast enough to "swap" on the fly (it would
  1711	have to be done during the HORIZONTAL retrace, which isn't all that long
  1712	<g>.)
  1713	 
  1714	John S.
  1715	       
  1716	
  1717	#: 21556 S13/Virtual Reality
  1718	    14-Nov-91  06:02:13
  1719	Sb: #21538-Position Sensors
  1720	Fm: John Swenson 75300,2136
  1721	To: Alexander Schipal 76137,326 (X)
  1722	
  1723	Actually it probably is NOT a laser gyro. All a lazer gyro is, is an almost
  1724	indestructable accelerometer. There are many other forms of accelerometers
  1725	which are MUCH cheaper than a laser one (and offer better resolution for
  1726	small size). I worked on one many years ago (so its probably much better and
  1727	cheaper today) which consisted of one of those integrated circuit pressure
  1728	sensors, with a tiny blob of mercury on the sensor surface (kept in place
  1729	with a little plastic buble). As the whole assembly moved the mercury would
  1730	push against the sensor, giving a nice proportional voltage to acceleration.
  1731	We used several of these in a little array to form a gyroscope, and put it in
  1732	a car and you could basically track it around town. After running around town
  1733	all day the absolute position error was about about 5 feet. The position
  1734	accuracy was primarily determined by how good the ADCs were. To get that good
  1735	in those days needed some awfully expensive ADCs. (the wole thing took up
  1736	about a cubic inch PLUS electronics of course <g>). I'm not sure if it was
  1737	sensitive enough for use on a glove though. The entire sensor array cost
  1738	about $60, but then there were the ADCs and other electronics, including a
  1739	computer, so the TOTAL cost was pretty high. It could be done a LOT cheaper
  1740	today. The sensors are a little cheaper, but the rest is much less.
  1741	 
  1742	John S.
  1743	       
  1744	
  1745	#: 21557 S13/Virtual Reality
  1746	    14-Nov-91  06:02:21
  1747	Sb: #21549-Rendering Engines
  1748	Fm: John Swenson 75300,2136
  1749	To: Alexander Schipal 76137,326 (X)
  1750	
  1751	Alexander,
  1752	I work for an ASIC company and have worked on a number of very high
  1753	performance proprietary graphics chips. The last one I worked on could do
  1754	150,000 tranformed, shaded 3d polygons per second, not too shabby
  1755	performance!
  1756	 
  1757	The last time I looked at a transputer design (several years ago) the
  1758	interchip communcations was so slow it killed the system (that was a DSP
  1759	application), we wound up doing it with an ASIC instead. It sounds like they
  1760	have improved a LOT since then. (I'm not sure I trust the 100 Mips number
  1761	though, there is so much specmanship going on its incredible, I also design
  1762	RISC processors so I'm constantly battling with marketing over ours and the
  1763	competition's "mips rating"). I think you just got my juices flowing again to
  1764	look into transputers.
  1765	 
  1766	Unfortunately for use by us on this forum, those graphics processor chips
  1767	have an NRE of $250,000 and unit costs of $300 or so (in volume).
  1768	 
  1769	John S.
